e-readers. Yet literature also offers powerful ways to change attitudes toward the environment. Puchner uncovers the ecological thinking behind the idea of world literature since the early nineteenth century, proposes a new way of reading in a warming world, shows how literature can help us recognize our shared humanity, and discusses the possible futures of storytelling.If we are to avoid environmental disaster, we must learn to tell the story of humans as a species responsible for global warming. Filled with important insights about the fundamental relationship between storytelling and the environment, Literature for a Changing Planet is a clarion call for readers and writers who care about the fate of life on the planet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aClimatic changes in literature. 0aEcocriticism. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aAdventure Story (play).  aAeneid.  aAge of Oil.  aAntihero.  aAratta.  aAuthor.  aBook.  aCaesar and Pompey.  aCity-state.  aClimate change.  aColonial empire.  aColonialism.  aColonization.  aComparative literature.  aConfucius.  aConquistador.  aCritical reading.  aDeep history.  aDisaster.  aDivine retribution.  aEcocriticism.  aEcology.  aEconomic globalization.  aEdition (book).  aEducation.  aEnkidu.  aEnlil.  aEnvironmental economics.  aEpic of Gilgamesh.  aEpic poetry.  aFan fiction.  aFlood myth.  aG. (novel).  aGenre.  aGlobal warming.  aGlobalization.  aHard Choices.  aHeadline.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHippie.  aHow It Happened.  aHumbaba.  aImmigration law.  aIndustrialisation.  aJataka tales.  aJohannes Gutenberg.  aLatin alphabet.  aLatin literature.  aLiterary criticism.  aLiterary realism.  aLiterature.  